title: For Sale/Trade:  Pre-ban Ruger Mini 14 with bayonet, ammo, new extras
postcontent:
This Series 182 Mini-14 is made to look as much as possible like the M1/M14 design that Ruger modeled their famous rifle on.  The highlight is an M4-style bayonet (if you are aware of Mini 14's at all, you know what a big deal having a bayonet is) mounted on a BRAND NEW M4-style muzzle brake with winged front sight.  Other modifications on the rifle include a rear tech peep sight and a leather/green web sling.  

Extras include:  
-Original front blade sight (beat up a fair bit before I got it)
-Choate birdcage flash hider which slides over original front sight
-5 magazines (2 metal 40 round, one OEM steel Ruger 20 round, one BRAND NEW ProMag 20 round, one original Ruger 5 round)
-2 BRAND NEW magazine couplers to connect magazines together for quicker mag changes
-An extra magazine reinforcement bracket (if you want to be able to swap between two different stocks quickly)
-100 rounds of loose .223 ammunition
-A brand new weather-resistant ammo can with rubber seal to keep out rain, humidity, etc
-A soft rifle sleeve to protect the gun

I have a handful more new Promag 20 round magazines I would sell, or throw in for the right trade.  I also have a couple hundred rounds of PMC X-Tac 5.56 ammunition I could include for sale.

I haven't fired it since installing the new sights/muzzle break so it will need to be sighted in on the range, but I did bore-sight it as well as possible using a laser so it shouldn't need too much adjustment.  This is an older, used rifle so there's some wear to it.  A few dings in the stock and butt, some wear on the bluing, etc.  There's also some deep scratches on the mounting handle on the bayonet where the hole had to be enlarged to fit over the muzzle brake.  But everything is in great working order, and this is a unique Mini-14 for your collection or use.

If you have any questions after reading this ad, feel free to drop me an e-mail.  I can send more pictures on request, or set up a time to meet.  I'm willing to do a little driving if you're coming from far away.  You must have a photo ID, and I prefer to deal with a CCW permit holder.

I would like cash, but am willing to entertain the idea of trades with cash up or down.

title: For Sale:  AR-15 to M16 drilling fixture for placing GI AUTO SEAR
postcontent:
The fixture is a drilling template made of machined steel that properly places the hole above the selector for the GI auto sear pin. A bolt is used to hold the fixture in place and the top of the fixture is aligned parallel with the top of the receiver to align sear pin hole. There is a washer that is used to allow the fixture to clear the ""selector stops"" on the receiver. There is still a small amount of milling that has to be done to allow for clearance for the sear in the receiver but that is explained in the fixture instructions and may be done with a dremel or on a drill press.

AR-15 to M16 drilling fixture for placing GI AUTO SEAR

title: For Sale/Trade:  Ati XTREME Machine  MFG. AT-47 AK 47
postcontent:
ati xtreme  MFG. AT-47 ak 47 

This rifle was the most interesting to me personally because it was crafted from a Ukrainian parts kit in my home state of Pennsylvania. It has a beautifully machined receiver and barrel and is carefully assembled in the quaint town of Grassflat, Pennsylvania. (They are distributed by ATI in Rochester, NY) Because the receiver is machined from a single billet of steel, it has a slightly different look (although it has the standard Soviet-Bloc wood furniture). Apparently the more precise construction gives this higher barrel pressure and better bullet velocity. It achieved the best 100 yard score (76.50) from the bench from ATI]

ANECDOTAL:
Broker—While I liked the smooth action, tightly controlled recoil, and accuracy – I thought the stock and grip too small and a bit awkward.

Mac—The good news for my friend is that Xtreme is designing a completely USA crafted AK with an adjustable stock (that’s a story for another day).

Deacon—The all American AK has been a long time coming. Since enactment of Bubba’s infamous assault weapons ban, perfectly good weapons have been mutilated overseas, stripped of the essentials and imported piecemeal to be rebuilt with selected U.S. components to make superior or inferior rifles depending on what side of the argument you choose to take. Having fired Soviet Bloc milled units in the past, I was pleased to see this rifle introduced by Xtreme Mfg.
The inherent greatness of the AK has been its low cost of manufacture, the simplicity of the machines needed to stamp out the parts by the score and readily field a combat ready weapon. Tolerances are loose by design and while this built in “rattle” provides us with a weather proof rifle, it also leaves us wanting for accuracy. The 7.62 X 39mm round has been badly maligned as being inaccurate. It ain’t the round, it’s the marriage of receiver, bolt and chamber that seats the round, properly spaces the projectile and preps it for our hands to send on its way. I have a friend in the North East who has been hunting deer for years
Comparisons of the AK-47

title: For Sale/Trade:  Ati. XTREME Machine  MFG. AT-47 AK 47 7.62x39
postcontent:
XTREME MFG. AT-47

This rifle was the most interesting to me personally because it was crafted from a Ukrainian parts kit in my home state of Pennsylvania. It has a beautifully machined receiver and barrel and is carefully assembled in the quaint town of Grassflat, Pennsylvania. (They are distributed by ATI in Rochester, NY) Because the receiver is machined from a single billet of steel, it has a slightly different look (although it has the standard Soviet-Bloc wood furniture). Apparently the more precise construction gives this higher barrel pressure and better bullet velocity. It achieved the best 100 yard score (76.50) from the bench from ATI]

ANECDOTAL:
Broker—While I liked the smooth action, tightly controlled recoil, and accuracy – I thought the stock and grip too small and a bit awkward.

Mac—The good news for my friend is that Xtreme is designing a completely USA crafted AK with an adjustable stock (that’s a story for another day).

Deacon—The all American AK has been a long time coming. Since enactment of Bubba’s infamous assault weapons ban, perfectly good weapons have been mutilated overseas, stripped of the essentials and imported piecemeal to be rebuilt with selected U.S. components to make superior or inferior rifles depending on what side of the argument you choose to take. Having fired Soviet Bloc milled units in the past, I was pleased to see this rifle introduced by Xtreme Mfg.
The inherent greatness of the AK has been its low cost of manufacture, the simplicity of the machines needed to stamp out the parts by the score and readily field a combat ready weapon. Tolerances are loose by design and while this built in “rattle” provides us with a weather proof rifle, it also leaves us wanting for accuracy. The 7.62 X 39mm round has been badly maligned as being inaccurate. It ain’t the round, it’s the marriage of receiver, bolt and chamber that seats the round, properly spaces the projectile and preps it for our hands to send on its way. I have a friend in the North East who has been hunting deer for years
Comparisons of the AK-47
Courtesy, The Warsaw Pact Panel

Broker: While I liked the Xtreme's smooth action, tightly controlled recoil, and accuracy, I thought the stock and grip were too small and awkward.

with what he calls “Russian rounds” from a Savage bolt action with a Douglas Barrel he had chambered for the 39mm. He takes a ribbing for using the stuff but everyone enjoys his venison stew and that’s where the laughter stops.
It seems from all objective results that Xtreme has tightened tolerances and given us a solid receiver that will shoot on par with any AR upper chambered in the same round. If they pass on importing foreign furniture and sights and build entirely from U.S. components we’ll all benefit.
Made in America. You have to love that. Sure there is room for improvement but the folks at Extreme are listening to the guys in the field and tweaking as I write.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Ati XTREME Machine  MFG. AT-47 AK 47
postcontent:
XTREME MFG. AT-47

This rifle was the most interesting to me personally because it was crafted from a Ukrainian parts kit in my home state of Pennsylvania. It has a beautifully machined receiver and barrel and is carefully assembled in the quaint town of Grassflat, Pennsylvania. (They are distributed by ATI in Rochester, NY) Because the receiver is machined from a single billet of steel, it has a slightly different look (although it has the standard Soviet-Bloc wood furniture). Apparently the more precise construction gives this higher barrel pressure and better bullet velocity. It achieved the best 100 yard score (76.50) from the bench from ATI]

ANECDOTAL:
Broker—While I liked the smooth action, tightly controlled recoil, and accuracy – I thought the stock and grip too small and a bit awkward.

Mac—The good news for my friend is that Xtreme is designing a completely USA crafted AK with an adjustable stock (that’s a story for another day).

Deacon—The all American AK has been a long time coming. Since enactment of Bubba’s infamous assault weapons ban, perfectly good weapons have been mutilated overseas, stripped of the essentials and imported piecemeal to be rebuilt with selected U.S. components to make superior or inferior rifles depending on what side of the argument you choose to take. Having fired Soviet Bloc milled units in the past, I was pleased to see this rifle introduced by Xtreme Mfg.
The inherent greatness of the AK has been its low cost of manufacture, the simplicity of the machines needed to stamp out the parts by the score and readily field a combat ready weapon. Tolerances are loose by design and while this built in “rattle” provides us with a weather proof rifle, it also leaves us wanting for accuracy. The 7.62 X 39mm round has been badly maligned as being inaccurate. It ain’t the round, it’s the marriage of receiver, bolt and chamber that seats the round, properly spaces the projectile and preps it for our hands to send on its way. I have a friend in the North East who has been hunting deer for years
Comparisons of the AK-47
Courtesy, The Warsaw Pact Panel

Broker: While I liked the Xtreme's smooth action, tightly controlled recoil, and accuracy, I thought the stock and grip were too small and awkward.

with what he calls “Russian rounds” from a Savage bolt action with a Douglas Barrel he had chambered for the 39mm. He takes a ribbing for using the stuff but everyone enjoys his venison stew and that’s where the laughter stops.
It seems from all objective results that Xtreme has tightened tolerances and given us a solid receiver that will shoot on par with any AR upper chambered in the same round. If they pass on importing foreign furniture and sights and build entirely from U.S. components we’ll all benefit.
Made in America. You have to love that. Sure there is room for improvement but the folks at Extreme are listening to the guys in the field and tweaking as I write.
Gun Reports Home >> Special Reports
Comparisons of the AK-47
Courtesy, The Warsaw Pact Panel

postcontent:
LSB#: 121012JR15

Make: Benelli Armi S.P.A. 

Model: M1 Super 90 

Serial Number: M259487

Year of Manufacture: 1996, Italian Proof Mark “BH” 

Caliber: 12 Gauge 3” or 2 ¾” Shells 

Action Type: Inertia-Operated Semi-Automatic

Markings: The left side of the barrel is marked “BENELLI ARMI S.P.A. – URBINO – MADE IN ITALY” . The right side of the barrel is marked “12 GA. 3” - FOR 2 ¾” OR 3” SHELLS / READ OWNER’S MANUAL BEFORE USING GUN”. The right side of the receiver is marked “HECKLER & KOCH.INC.-STERLING.VA.-MADE IN ITALY”. The left side of the receiver is marked “12 GA.-M1 SUPER 90- BENELLI -ITALY”. The underside of the receiver is marked with the serial number and Italian proof marks. The bolt is marked “BENELLI ARMI SYSTEM”. 

Barrel Length: 18 ½ ” 

Choke: Improved Cylinder .722

Sights / Optics: This shotgun is mounted with tactical ghost ring dipolar sights. 

Stock Configuration & Condition: The stocks are synthetic with a pistol grip. The checkering on the forend and ribbing on the pistol grip are sharp. There are very few light handling scuff marks on the buttstock and forend. This shotgun was very well cared for. It likely spent a majority of its life in storage, waiting to be used. The LOP measures 14 ¼” from the trigger to the Benelli rubber recoil pad. The recoil pad is soft and pliable and fits the buttstock nicely. The stocks rate in about Excellent overall condition. 

Type of Finish: Matte

Finish Originality: Factory Original 

Bore Condition: The bore is Bright and Smooth. There is no apparent erosion. 

Overall Condition: This shotgun retains about 98% of its metal finish. The balance of the finish shows very light handling marks. Most of the marks are on the leading edges of the rear sight and on the left side of the receiver. The non-reflective finish makes these marks only visable at certain angles and do not take away from the overall appearance. The Screw heads are sharp. The markings are clear. Overall, this shotgun rates in about Excellent condition. 

Mechanics: The action functions correctly. We did not fire this shotgun. 

Box, Paperwork & Accessories: Sling

Our Assessment: This would make a great tactical home defense or 3 gun competition gun. Already boasting ghost ring dipolar sights, sling, and pistol grip, you’re a box of shotgun shells away from a competition grade shooter. Due to the inertia recoil system, the M1 should use heavier loads to cycle. However, the operating system uses the recoil giving the feel of shooting much lighter loads in comparison to a gas operating auto loader. Take a look at the top 3 gun shooters on YouTube, they all use a Benelli. The shotgun is in excellent condition and should not get passed up this Holiday season. You could even send this one to Taran Tactical Innovations and have the best tactical shotgun imaginable built.

title: For Sale:  Juggernaut Arms - FN FS2000
postcontent:
Location: 240 Freeport Suite #2
             Sparks, NV 89431

Manufacturer: FN
Model: FS 2000
Caliber: 5.56x45 NATO
Capacity: (30) Standard AR Magazines
Condition: New in Box


The F2000 is a modular weapon system; its principal component is a compact 5.56×45mm NATO-caliber assault rifle configured in a bullpup layout. The F2000 is a selective fire weapon operating from a closed bolt.
The rifle consists of two main assemblies: the barreled receiver group and the frame, coupled together by means of an axis pin located above the trigger guard. The barrel group has an integral MIL-STD-1913 Picatinny rail used to mount optical sights. The frame or lower receiver contains the trigger group, the bolt and bolt carrier assembly, return mechanism and magazine well. A removable handguard is installed in front of the trigger which completes and encloses the trigger guard.
[edit]Features
The FS2000 is a gas operated, semi-automatic and ambidextrous bullpup rifle. Both the safety system and trigger mechanism were adopted from the P90 personal defense weapon; the selector toggle is a rotating disc located below the trigger. The fire selector doubles as the weapon’s manual safety and secures the firearm against accidental discharge (the selector/safety disc has 3 settings: "S"—safe, "1"—semi-automatic mode, "A"—fully automatic fire). The "safe" setting disables the trigger. The hammers, group pins, and springs are steel while all other components are nylon injection molding. The shell of the rifle is made of composite materials.
The F2000 is fed from standard NATO box magazines (STANAG 4179) with a 30-round cartridge capacity using 5.56×45mm ammunition. The magazine catch/release button is installed symmetrically in the pistol grip, in front of the magazine; the magazine catch is operated by an oversized actuator used when wearing NBC gloves. The F2000 is not configured from the factory to have a drop-free magazine system due to the friction from the removable dust gaskets. The magazine needs to be pulled out manually.
The rifle does not have a hold-open device; the bolt does not stay back after the last round is fired. The cocking handle is placed on the left side of the receiver, just above the handguard, and can be operated by left-handed shooters. There are no access points for the possible ingress of dirt or debris; the cocking handle slot is sealed.
The weapon’s primary sight is a telescopic sight with a fixed 1.6× magnification (the reticle also enables use in low-light conditions) contained in a plastic housing above the receiver (mounted on the MIL-STD-1913 rail), the secondary sight is a non-adjustable fixed notch and front blade, molded into the optical sight housing cover. The sight cover and sight module can be quickly removed to reveal the Picatinny rail.
The rifle’s chromed hammer-forged steel barrel is stated to retain accuracy after 20,000 normal (non-sustained) rounds. The barrel also features a flash suppressor with an angled cut at the tip which directs the muzzle blast upward, compensating for muzzle rise. The F2000 has an optional bayonet lug mounted near the muzzle, and an adjustable gas regulator with two settings: "normal" for standard ammunition meeting NATO specifications, and "adverse"—used to send an increased volume of gas into the system to ensure proper functioning when fouled or when using low pressure ammunition.
